---
import { getCollection } from "astro:content";
import Card from "../components/Card.astro";
import Search from "../components/Search.astro";
import BaseLayout from "../layouts/BaseLayout.astro";
import RecentUpdates from "../components/RecentUpdates.astro";

const patterns = await getCollection("patterns", ({ data }) => {
  return data.draft !== true;
});
---

<BaseLayout showHeader={false}>
  <header class="space-y-3 pt-16 text-balance">
    <h1
      class="text-xl font-bold uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-sky-700 dark:text-sky-300 pb-3"
    >
      Frontend Patterns
    </h1>
    <p class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-semibold leading-tight pb-10">
      The definitive pattern catalog for modern web development.
    </p>

    <p class="text-base md:text-lg">
      The comprehensive frontend architecture pattern library. 150+ patterns
      across components, performance, testing, accessibility, security, and
      scaling, with implementations for React, Vue, and Svelte.
    </p>
  </header>

  <Search />

  <section>
    <h2
      class="text-3xl md:text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-slate-900 dark:text-slate-100 pb-5"
    >
      Browse Patterns
    </h2>

    <div
      class="grid gap-6 sm:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 auto-rows-[minmax(0,auto)]"
    >
      <Card title="Component Patterns">
        How to structure, compose, and organize UI components.
      </Card>

      <Card title="Performance Patterns">
        Making apps fast: loading, rendering, runtime performance.
      </Card>

      <Card title="State Management Patterns">
        Where state lives, how it flows, how to manage it.
      </Card>

      <Card title="Accessibility Patterns">
        Making apps usable for everyone
      </Card>

      <Card title="Testing Patterns"> How to test effectively at scale. </Card>

      <Card title="Data Fetching Patterns">
        Getting data from APIs, caching, synchronization.
      </Card>

      <Card title="Security Patterns">
        Protecting users and applications.
      </Card>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="space-y-6">
    <div class="flex items-center justify-between">
      <h2
        class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-slate-900 dark:text-slate-100"
      >
        Recent updates
      </h2>
    </div>

    <RecentUpdates patterns={patterns} />
  </section>

  <section>
    <h2
      class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-slate-900 dark:text-slate-100 pb-5"
    >
      What is a pattern?
    </h2>

    <p class="text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300 pb-10">
      A pattern is a reusable solution to a common problem in software design.
      Patterns provide a template for how to solve a problem in a way that has
      been proven to be effective. They are not specific implementations, but
      rather general concepts that can be adapted to fit different contexts and
      requirements.
    </p>

    <h2
      class="text-2xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-slate-900 dark:text-slate-100 pb-5"
    >
      Why is a definitive frontend architecture pattern library needed?
    </h2>

    <p class="text-slate-700 dark:text-slate-300">
      As frontend development becomes increasingly complex, with a myriad of
      frameworks, libraries, and tools available, developers face challenges in
      choosing the right approaches for building scalable, maintainable, and
      efficient applications. A definitive pattern library serves as a
      centralized resource that consolidates best practices and proven
      solutions, helping developers navigate this complexity. It promotes
      consistency across projects, facilitates knowledge sharing within the
      community, and aids in onboarding new team members by providing clear
      guidelines. Ultimately, such a library empowers developers to make
      informed decisions, leading to higher-quality software and more efficient
      development processes.
    </p>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>
